WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:07.510 --> 00:00:12.510
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: Good evening
and welcome to the main event.

00:00:12.510 --> 00:00:16.230
The last program of the
evening here in the ballroom.

00:00:16.230 --> 00:00:17.820
My name is Ron Elving.

00:00:17.820 --> 00:00:21.650
I am an editor correspondent
podcaster at NPR

00:00:21.650 --> 00:00:25.810
and also a full-time, thank you,
and also a full-time faculty member

00:00:25.810 --> 00:00:28.600
at American University
School of Public Affairs.

00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:32.320
And it is my very great
pleasure to be here this evening

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:37.940
with John Aloysius Farrell;
Jack Farrell to his friends,

00:00:37.940 --> 00:00:40.770
and he has written his third book.

00:00:40.770 --> 00:00:45.820
His first book was called "Clarence
Darrow, Attorney for the Damned."

00:00:45.820 --> 00:00:48.080
Now I think you should buy
that book just for the title.

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:53.060
His second book was called "Tip
O'Neal and the Democratic Century,"

00:00:53.060 --> 00:00:57.960
and then he turned to
Richard Nixon, "The Life."

00:00:57.960 --> 00:01:02.630
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: Because he's
such a popular character.

00:01:02.630 --> 00:01:04.640
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: Because
of that trajectory,

00:01:04.640 --> 00:01:09.380
I have to ask what made
you turn to Dick Nixon?

00:01:09.380 --> 00:01:12.880
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: I was
drawn to his story.

00:01:12.880 --> 00:01:16.330
The original subtitle for the
book was "Mr. Richard Nixon,

00:01:16.330 --> 00:01:19.950
An American Tragedy," and I was
struck when I did the research

00:01:19.950 --> 00:01:23.240
that people like Henry Kissinger
and Elliot Richardson would write

00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:27.920
in their diaries or talk on
the phone with each other

00:01:27.920 --> 00:01:32.200
and as Watergate was collapsing
around him, they would say,

00:01:32.200 --> 00:01:34.660
"This is really like
classic Greek tragedy."

00:01:34.660 --> 00:01:40.950 position:56%
This is really a Shakespearean scene
of someone who has so many gifts,

00:01:40.950 --> 00:01:46.370
and yet this amazing tragic
flaw which ended up bringing him

00:01:46.370 --> 00:01:51.740
down in quite a Shakespearean
manner.

00:01:51.740 --> 00:01:53.860
He was Iago to this own Othello.

00:01:53.860 --> 00:01:57.680
He was always whispering in his
own ear, "You're not good enough.

00:01:57.680 --> 00:01:59.460
They hate you.

00:01:59.460 --> 00:02:03.470
They're against me," and in
the end, it destroyed him,

00:02:03.470 --> 00:02:07.920
and he had that one final
moment of recognition.

00:02:07.920 --> 00:02:11.520 position:56%
Some of you may remember on the last
day that he was in the White House

00:02:11.520 --> 00:02:16.400 position:56%
when he addressed his staff and
family in the East Room and he said,

00:02:16.400 --> 00:02:19.360
"Remember others may hate you

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:22.820
but if you hate them then you
destroy yourself," and so,

00:02:22.820 --> 00:02:25.930
there's this wonderful moment
of self-recognition when he sees

00:02:25.930 --> 00:02:30.410
that that the tragic flaw has
brought him down in just the way

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:35.480
that he feared the most, and yet
in the end that's what got him.

00:02:35.480 --> 00:02:37.070
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: I'm
struck by your comparison

00:02:37.070 --> 00:02:39.290
to Iago to his own Othello.

00:02:39.290 --> 00:02:41.670
I don't believe that
line is in the book.

00:02:41.670 --> 00:02:45.320
I think you had said it on another
occasion and I had looked for it

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:48.170
in the book and I don't
believe I found it.

00:02:48.170 --> 00:02:50.600
Is that something you have
thought of since writing the book

00:02:50.600 --> 00:02:52.120
and what does it mean to you?

00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:53.420
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: No.

00:02:53.420 --> 00:02:57.160
Actually when you write a proposal
for a book, you sort of try to come

00:02:57.160 --> 00:03:02.120 position:56%
up with analogies to what this story
is, and when I wrote the proposal

00:03:02.120 --> 00:03:04.490
for Double Day, that
was in the proposal.

00:03:04.490 --> 00:03:05.970
I didn't use it in the book.

00:03:05.970 --> 00:03:08.900
I probably should have because
as I went back and prepared to go

00:03:08.900 --> 00:03:11.170
out on the book tour, I
came across that line.

00:03:11.170 --> 00:03:15.390
I said, "Hey, this is a pretty
good line," and I've used it.

00:03:15.390 --> 00:03:17.640
But if you remember the play,

00:03:17.640 --> 00:03:23.380
Othello was this great general
and Iago his lieutenant.

00:03:23.380 --> 00:03:26.620
Very jealous of him and
starts whispering in his ear

00:03:26.620 --> 00:03:33.780 position:56%
and Iago puts this paranoia in
Othello, and in the end Othello ends

00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:37.360
up killing his beautiful
wife Desdemona

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:39.970
because Iago was so
good at doing that.

00:03:39.970 --> 00:03:48.050
So Nixon always had this
susceptibility of telling himself

00:03:48.050 --> 00:03:50.150
over and over again,
"I'm not good enough,"

00:03:50.150 --> 00:03:54.290
and one of the most heart
[inaudible] examples of this is

00:03:54.290 --> 00:03:57.940
when he comes back from China,
and he's accomplished everything

00:03:57.940 --> 00:04:00.710
that he wanted to do in his life.

00:04:00.710 --> 00:04:03.200
He's become president
against all these odds.

00:04:03.200 --> 00:04:06.980
Come from the backwoods
of California

00:04:06.980 --> 00:04:09.090
to become president
of the United States.

00:04:09.090 --> 00:04:12.650
He wants to be a great man
and he sees this opportunity

00:04:12.650 --> 00:04:15.650
in the Cold War to drive
a wedge between Red China

00:04:15.650 --> 00:04:20.780
and the Soviet Union, and to bring
China into the family of nations.

00:04:20.780 --> 00:04:23.730
And long before he was president,
he wrote about this in an article

00:04:23.730 --> 00:04:25.830
in the Foreign Affairs Magazine,

00:04:25.830 --> 00:04:28.890
talking about how this
new century was going

00:04:28.890 --> 00:04:31.420
to be a century --
an information age.

00:04:31.420 --> 00:04:34.740
This is Richard Nixon in 1965.

00:04:34.740 --> 00:04:37.060
An information age
dominated by computers

00:04:37.060 --> 00:04:40.980
and that the old Communist
monolithic societies would not be

00:04:40.980 --> 00:04:45.010
able to compete with the
nimbleness of science that's going

00:04:45.010 --> 00:04:46.900
to be needed in the 21st century.

00:04:46.900 --> 00:04:50.190
So he sees this happening
as he's president.

00:04:50.190 --> 00:04:51.810
He goes to China.

00:04:51.810 --> 00:04:56.380
He makes this amazing breakthrough,
and he comes back and he's talking

00:04:56.380 --> 00:04:59.830
to Henry Kissinger on one of
these infamous White House tapes,

00:04:59.830 --> 00:05:02.290
and Iago starts to whisper.

00:05:02.290 --> 00:05:04.640
And he says, "You know Henry,

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:07.260
the American people
are a bunch of sheep.

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:10.630
They watched me on television with
all that handshaking and stuff

00:05:10.630 --> 00:05:13.610
in China, and you and I know it
really doesn't mean a thing."

00:05:13.610 --> 00:05:16.720
And this is Richard Nixon
not really being cynical

00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:19.940
about the American people but
badmouthing himself because he had

00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:21.970
such a sense of inferiority.

00:05:21.970 --> 00:05:25.220
So that's where I -- I should
have used it in the book.

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:26.520
It is a good line.

00:05:26.520 --> 00:05:28.240 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: And then you
