that took that native paranoia

00:27:42.810 --> 00:27:48.380
within his spirit and
accentuated it in Washington.

00:27:48.380 --> 00:27:51.670
But it was there from the beginning
because that first campaign,

00:27:51.670 --> 00:27:54.520
another little piece of the
jigsaw puzzle that I found was

00:27:54.520 --> 00:27:57.690
that Nixon loved to make lists.

00:27:57.690 --> 00:28:01.650 position:56%
He would sit in an armchair, put
his feet up with a yellow legal pad,

00:28:01.650 --> 00:28:04.610 position:56%
all the way even through his
presidency, and just write out lists

00:28:04.610 --> 00:28:07.130
and thoughts on yellow legal pads.

00:28:07.130 --> 00:28:11.210
And one of these I found, one of
the first ones when he came back

00:28:11.210 --> 00:28:14.580
from the war, and he was running
for Congress, a complete unknown,

00:28:14.580 --> 00:28:17.120
and there one of the
things to do is like, okay,

00:28:17.120 --> 00:28:21.630
go to the rotary meetings, stop by
the local newspaper and buy an ad,

00:28:21.630 --> 00:28:25.990
set up a voter organization in
such and such a neighborhood.

00:28:25.990 --> 00:28:29.970
Put spies in the Voorhis camp.

00:28:29.970 --> 00:28:32.250
This is [inaudible].

00:28:32.250 --> 00:28:36.820
There was something there from the
very beginning that eventually grew

00:28:36.820 --> 00:28:41.710
and flourished and erupted
in Watergate, but all along,

00:28:41.710 --> 00:28:48.650 position:56%
he definitely had opposition from
the liberal press that egged him on.

00:28:48.650 --> 00:28:51.120
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: And he always
believed, perhaps because of

00:28:51.120 --> 00:28:54.550
that early experience that he
had with individual publishers,

00:28:54.550 --> 00:28:59.800 position:56%
editorialists, reporters, that every
newspaper decided whether they were

00:28:59.800 --> 00:29:02.090
with you or against
you and that was it.

00:29:02.090 --> 00:29:03.910
Not just on the editorial page.

00:29:03.910 --> 00:29:05.510
Not just in terms of endorsement,

00:29:05.510 --> 00:29:08.610
but in terms of how they
covered you in the news.

00:29:08.610 --> 00:29:12.780
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: And then he had
some horrible misfortune in 1960.

00:29:12.780 --> 00:29:18.380 position:56%
He runs against the most charismatic
candidate of the time, Jack Kennedy,

00:29:18.380 --> 00:29:22.220
who loved the press, who was
a reporter, who could relate

00:29:22.220 --> 00:29:26.230
with the press, and there is
absolutely no doubt in history

00:29:26.230 --> 00:29:31.890 position:56%
that the 1960 press core, the actual
reporters were sided with Kennedy.

00:29:31.890 --> 00:29:36.930
Nixon got more editorial
endorsements and Nixon was,

00:29:36.930 --> 00:29:39.090
who had used television
so masterfully

00:29:39.090 --> 00:29:42.350
in the famous Checker's
speech was betrayed

00:29:42.350 --> 00:29:44.510
by his performance in the debates.

00:29:44.510 --> 00:29:48.120
So there were balancing
factors in the media

00:29:48.120 --> 00:29:51.070
but definitely the campaign
reporters that he dealt

00:29:51.070 --> 00:29:56.370
with every day were very much pro
Kennedy and there's really no doubt

00:29:56.370 --> 00:30:00.590
in history that this reinforced
his idea that reporters were

00:30:00.590 --> 00:30:03.080
at least ideologically on the tape.

00:30:03.080 --> 00:30:05.180
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: And I want to
give you all an opportunity

00:30:05.180 --> 00:30:09.400
to ask questions so I'll just ask
you one more as people come forward

00:30:09.400 --> 00:30:11.570
and you can line up here at
the microphone so we have one

00:30:11.570 --> 00:30:14.440
on either side if you'd
like to ask question.

00:30:14.440 --> 00:30:20.020
But let me just ask you, the
name of Donald Trump has come up,

00:30:20.020 --> 00:30:24.080
and it's difficult to not draw
parallels between these characters.

00:30:24.080 --> 00:30:26.980
Other people have done some between
the character of Richard Nixon

00:30:26.980 --> 00:30:28.280
and the character of Donald Trump.

00:30:28.280 --> 00:30:31.760 position:56%
The media element is an obvious one.

00:30:31.760 --> 00:30:35.840
What else do you draw as a
biography and as a reporter,

00:30:35.840 --> 00:30:38.780
what else do you draw as
lessons from this period

00:30:38.780 --> 00:30:41.840
when we come to our own era?

00:30:41.840 --> 00:30:43.280
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: I don't
think there's a lot

00:30:43.280 --> 00:30:45.980
of comparison between the two men.

00:30:45.980 --> 00:30:50.590
Nixon was definitely a
foreign policy intellectual.

00:30:50.590 --> 00:30:53.220
He read and wrote books.

00:30:53.220 --> 00:30:58.220
Because he had served as
Eisenhower's vice-president,

00:30:58.220 --> 00:31:02.960 position:56%
he had a great dignity and respect
for the office that didn't blind him

00:31:02.960 --> 00:31:05.140
to commit the sins of Watergate,

00:31:05.140 --> 00:31:11.730
but still he would
never treat it vulgarly.

00:31:11.730 --> 00:31:15.550
So in that regard, there's
really not a lot of comparison

00:31:15.550 --> 00:31:18.820
between the -- I don't see a lot
of comparison between the two men.

00:31:18.820 --> 00:31:22.680
They both campaigned and perhaps
Trump took this from Nixon,

00:31:22.680 --> 00:31:25.290
with sort of this politics
of grievance and resentment.

00:31:25.290 --> 00:31:28.750
And in fact, at times, Trump,
when he was campaigning,

00:31:28.750 --> 00:31:31.320
he even used the phrases
that Nixon used.

00:31:31.320 --> 00:31:32.620
You know, "It's going to be a law

00:31:32.620 --> 00:31:36.350
and order administration,"
and things like that.

00:31:36.350 --> 00:31:43.240
And the sins that Nixon was charged
with or that had been alleged

00:31:43.240 --> 00:31:48.050
about our President
Trump are very similar.

00:31:48.050 --> 00:31:53.440 position:56%
The Saturday night massacre in which
Nixon fired the special prosecutor

00:31:53.440 --> 00:31:57.400
is compared very closely
to Nixon firing the --

00:31:57.400 --> 00:32:01.130
Trump firing the FBI director
who was leading the investigation

00:32:01.130 --> 00:32:03.130
into Nixon, and there's
all this talk

00:32:03.130 --> 00:32:06.640
that perhaps Trump will fire
today's special prosecutor.

00:32:06.640 --> 00:32:10.840
So it's more of a superficial
resemblance I think

00:32:10.840 --> 00:32:12.980
than an actual one.

00:32:12.980 --> 00:32:14.280
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: Thank you.

00:32:14.280 --> 00:32:15.580
And we will take your
questions, sir.

00:32:15.580 --> 00:32:17.300
This gentleman on the left.

00:32:17.300 --> 00:32:19.430
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much.

00:32:19.430 --> 00:32:22.720
This concerns the five
Watergate burglars.

00:32:22.720 --> 00:32:24.800
I had the pleasure this week

00:32:24.800 --> 00:32:27.980
of attending a continuing legal
education program presented

00:32:27.980 --> 00:32:32.470
by John Dean, and he
said very definitively

00:32:32.470 --> 00:32:35.440
without any hesitation whatsoever,

00:32:35.440 --> 00:32:43.670
that if the five burglars had
not been apprehended breaking

00:32:43.670 --> 00:32:47.340
into the democratic
headquarters at the Watergate,

00:32:47.340 --> 00:32:54.480
they had another place to go that
very evening, and that other place

00:32:54.480 --> 00:33:01.150
to go was McGovern
headquarters because people

00:33:01.150 --> 00:33:05.780
in the White House had expressed an
interest in knowing what was going

00:33:05.780 --> 00:33:11.980
on there, and the point that
he made is that while the break

00:33:11.980 --> 00:33:16.860
in at the DMC did not emanate
from the White House per se,

00:33:16.860 --> 00:33:21.030
the cover up did but
not the DNC break in.

00:33:21.030 --> 00:33:24.720
The subsequent break in that
never got a chance to happen

00:33:24.720 --> 00:33:30.000
at McGovern headquarters did
emanate from certain individuals

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:33.260
in the White House and
therefore ironically

00:33:33.260 --> 00:33:38.570
if the five guys had managed to
make it to destination number two,

00:33:38.570 --> 00:33:43.110
then the Watergate house of cards
might have come down sooner.

00:33:43.110 --> 00:33:47.410
I'd very much appreciate
your addressing that.

00:33:47.410 --> 00:33:52.500
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: There are no
questions anymore about Watergate.

00:33:52.500 --> 00:33:57.050
The tapes show Nixon talking
to Bob Holden saying, "Bob,

00:33:57.050 --> 00:33:58.420
we need more wiretapping.

00:33:58.420 --> 00:34:02.920
You need to go out now and follow
the Democratic candidates."

00:34:02.920 --> 00:34:07.010
And in this vast flood of paper
that's been released in the last 30

00:34:07.010 --> 00:34:11.090
or 40 years, you have evidence

00:34:11.090 --> 00:34:13.120
that it wasn't just
McGovern headquarters.

00:34:13.120 --> 00:34:15.900
That they also -- Muskie
was the frontrunner.

00:34:15.900 --> 00:34:19.950
They had opened up an office next
to Muskie headquarters to serve

00:34:19.950 --> 00:34:23.470
as a listening post
and had gotten --

00:34:23.470 --> 00:34:26.790
by putting spies in the Muskie
camp had gotten floor plans

00:34:26.790 --> 00:34:30.310 position:56%
of Muskie showing where the
different desks and telephones were.

00:34:30.310 --> 00:34:35.220
So this was almost everyone of
Nixon's aides at the White House

00:34:35.220 --> 00:34:38.560
with the exception of Henry
Kissinger had some sort

00:34:38.560 --> 00:34:41.280
of involvement in one
of these dirty tricks.

00:34:41.280 --> 00:34:44.520
It was a massive campaign.

00:34:44.520 --> 00:34:49.440
And indeed, as you say, it's a
signal of what clowns Gordon Liddy

00:34:49.440 --> 00:34:52.710
and Howard Hunt were that they
thought that they could break

00:34:52.710 --> 00:34:58.370
into the Democratic National
Committee at 11:00 p.m.

00:34:58.370 --> 00:35:02.960
and burglar it and install
bugs and take photographs

00:35:02.960 --> 00:35:06.600
and then still be fresh
enough and energetic enough

00:35:06.600 --> 00:35:08.790
that at 3:00 a.m. they would
drive up to Capitol Hillis

00:35:08.790 --> 00:35:12.280
to McGovern headquarters which they
had tried unsuccessfully to break

00:35:12.280 --> 00:35:16.390
into three times already and break
successfully do it the same night.

00:35:16.390 --> 00:35:19.720 position:56%
And they were doing it because Liddy
and Hunt had loaned all this money

00:35:19.720 --> 00:35:24.530
that they had been given and their
bosses called them in and Mitchell

00:35:24.530 --> 00:35:27.440
and others were saying,
"Where's the fruits

00:35:27.440 --> 00:35:31.000
of what we're spending money
on," and so they panicked,

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:33.970
and they did incredibly
stupid things throughout

00:35:33.970 --> 00:35:35.270
that whole episode.

00:35:35.270 --> 00:35:36.780
But Dean is right in that regard.

00:35:36.780 --> 00:35:39.150
&gt;&gt; He also said that
the motive for breaking

00:35:39.150 --> 00:35:41.640
into the McGovern headquarters
was to see

00:35:41.640 --> 00:35:44.890
if the McGovern people had come
across some of the information

00:35:44.890 --> 00:35:49.180
about the Elsburg psychiatric
break in, and they wanted to know

00:35:49.180 --> 00:35:53.860
if they were going to get hit with
[inaudible] material from them.

00:35:53.860 --> 00:35:55.940
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: I wouldn't
argue with him about that.

00:35:55.940 --> 00:35:57.560
I know that part of
the motive for the --

00:35:57.560 --> 00:35:59.600
I think there were many
motives for what they wanted.

00:35:59.600 --> 00:36:01.780
They basically wanted
anything and everything.

00:36:01.780 --> 00:36:05.520
You can't just say, well
Watergate just happened because so

00:36:05.520 --> 00:36:07.900
and so wanted this
particular piece of paper.

00:36:07.900 --> 00:36:09.880
There were lots of things
that they were looking for.

00:36:09.880 --> 00:36:11.370
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: Thank you, and
thank you for your question.

00:36:11.370 --> 00:36:13.080
Let's take one from over here.

00:36:13.080 --> 00:36:15.180
&gt;&gt; So I guess some of
the strangest moments

00:36:15.180 --> 00:36:20.350 position:56%
from a really strange presidency was
in, I think, 1970 after the bombing

00:36:20.350 --> 00:36:24.160
of Cambodia and he has this weird
press conference, and he's staying

00:36:24.160 --> 00:36:27.840
up all night calling like 50
different people and he decides

00:36:27.840 --> 00:36:30.380
to go to the Lincoln
Memorial and talk face-to-face

00:36:30.380 --> 00:36:32.300
with a bunch of student protestors.

00:36:32.300 --> 00:36:35.210
And I think it was in the
Oliver Stone film too.

00:36:35.210 --> 00:36:36.510
They kind of showed that as well.

00:36:36.510 --> 00:36:38.890
I was wondering, what
did you take from that?

00:36:38.890 --> 00:36:42.530
What do you think Richard Nixon
was looking for in that encounter?

00:36:42.530 --> 00:36:43.830
Why do you think he
went [inaudible]?

00:36:43.830 --> 00:36:46.870
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: I think the
key to that encounter happens

00:36:46.870 --> 00:36:50.040 position:56%
after he leaves the Lincoln Memorial
and he goes up to the capital.

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:54.570
And he's up at the capital and
he tries to get into the senate.

00:36:54.570 --> 00:36:57.160
He can't, it's locked, but he
goes to the house representatives

00:36:57.160 --> 00:37:00.660
and he's brought his valet because
the whole purpose of this jaunt is

00:37:00.660 --> 00:37:04.960
to show Manila the glories
of Washington at night.

00:37:04.960 --> 00:37:10.480
And so, he has him get up --
Nixon sits in the chairs below

00:37:10.480 --> 00:37:14.950
and he has Manila get up on
the dias and give a speech.

00:37:14.950 --> 00:37:18.960
And as they're walking out and
leaving, there's a cleaning lady,

00:37:18.960 --> 00:37:23.490
and she comes over and
she's carrying her bible.

00:37:23.490 --> 00:37:27.000
And she says, "Hi, Mr. President."

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:29.270
I can't remember whether she
asked him to sign the bible

00:37:29.270 --> 00:37:33.790
or he just notices it and he says,

00:37:33.790 --> 00:37:37.220
"Read your bible and
you'll be a saint.

00:37:37.220 --> 00:37:42.260
My mother was a saint," and Nixon's
mother throughout his life was sort

00:37:42.260 --> 00:37:45.660
of his conscience, and she
had died only, I think,

00:37:45.660 --> 00:37:49.260
two years before he
finally won the presidency.

00:37:49.260 --> 00:37:53.560
And throughout that night,
there's references in his ramblings

00:37:53.560 --> 00:37:59.460
about his mom and you can make
sort of the psychological argument

00:37:59.460 --> 00:38:04.300
that he was very concerned about
the fact that she would not approve

00:38:04.300 --> 00:38:08.720
of him expanding the war in the
way that he did into Cambodia.

00:38:08.720 --> 00:38:14.610
That the death of the four students
at Kent State would be something

00:38:14.610 --> 00:38:16.380
that she would really object to

00:38:16.380 --> 00:38:23.010
and that he was expressing not only
tension but also some small bit

00:38:23.010 --> 00:38:25.800
of guilt and shame about his mom.

00:38:25.800 --> 00:38:27.600
That's at least the way
that I've always interpreted

00:38:27.600 --> 00:38:30.540
that remark; my mother was a saint.

00:38:30.540 --> 00:38:32.300
You be a saint too.

00:38:32.300 --> 00:38:35.020
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: Let's see if we can
get to a couple more over here.

00:38:35.020 --> 00:38:36.320 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Perhaps it would have been better

00:38:36.320 --> 00:38:38.650
if Richard Nixon had
never become president.

00:38:38.650 --> 00:38:42.460
But given that he did,
I've always believed

00:38:42.460 --> 00:38:45.340
that it would have been better for
Nixon, for the Republican party

00:38:45.340 --> 00:38:51.230
and for the country, if he had
won in 1960 rather than 1968.

00:38:51.230 --> 00:38:54.140
Is that a sentiment
that you share or not?

00:38:54.140 --> 00:38:57.050
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: Nixon was amazing
in that all three times he ran

00:38:57.050 --> 00:39:01.290
for president, he ran as the more
moderate candidate in the race.

00:39:01.290 --> 00:39:02.650
He was more moderate than JFK.

00:39:02.650 --> 00:39:06.820
He was more moderate than George
Wallace and later Hubert Humphrey

00:39:06.820 --> 00:39:12.310
and he certainly was more moderate
than George McGovern in 1972.

00:39:12.310 --> 00:39:16.430
So he always represented
sort of the stayed center.

00:39:16.430 --> 00:39:20.420
And if he had gotten
elected in 1960,

00:39:20.420 --> 00:39:23.170
I don't know how he
would have handled Cuba.

00:39:23.170 --> 00:39:27.350
It's awful to play those
hands out in retrospect.

00:39:27.350 --> 00:39:30.640
I know that he would have
supported the Bay of Pigs invasion.

00:39:30.640 --> 00:39:33.500
He always claimed that he
never would have let it go

00:39:33.500 --> 00:39:35.820
on in a half assessed
way the way Kennedy did.

00:39:35.820 --> 00:39:38.190
It would have been a full
scale invasion the way

00:39:38.190 --> 00:39:40.600
that Ike invaded Normandy.

00:39:40.600 --> 00:39:44.020
So you still might have
had the missiles of October

00:39:44.020 --> 00:39:47.660
but they might have been
the missiles of April 1961.

00:39:47.660 --> 00:39:51.170
Instead if this provoked a
super power confrontation.

00:39:51.170 --> 00:39:58.080
But he definitely was
a calmer man in 1960.

00:39:58.080 --> 00:39:59.380
Not a great candidate.

00:39:59.380 --> 00:40:01.770
Lost that race for a reason.

00:40:01.770 --> 00:40:05.000
Became really close
and actually believed

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:06.880
that he had actually won it.

00:40:06.880 --> 00:40:08.180
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: Thank you.

00:40:08.180 --> 00:40:09.480
Sir?

00:40:09.480 --> 00:40:10.780
&gt;&gt; So you had said that one

00:40:10.780 --> 00:40:13.840
of Nixon's most admirable
traits was his resilience.

00:40:13.840 --> 00:40:16.090
So there were two great
comebacks in his career.

00:40:16.090 --> 00:40:18.880
One was after losing the
presidency in 1960 and then

00:40:18.880 --> 00:40:20.830
after Watergate of course.

00:40:20.830 --> 00:40:24.610
How did he go about
engineering these comebacks

00:40:24.610 --> 00:40:26.610
and why did the American
people largely accept them?

00:40:26.610 --> 00:40:30.950
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: The first comeback

00:40:30.950 --> 00:40:34.430
which Pat Buchanan has written a
book called "The Greatest Comeback"

00:40:34.430 --> 00:40:35.730
and I would say that that's true.

00:40:35.730 --> 00:40:38.190
Maybe the greatest comeback
in political history.

00:40:38.190 --> 00:40:43.890
To come back from 1960 to 68.

00:40:43.890 --> 00:40:50.600
In 1968, you can't believe the
chaos that Americans had been in,

00:40:50.600 --> 00:40:55.020
and what they wanted was just some
sort of semblance of normalcy.

00:40:55.020 --> 00:40:59.230
And you find that all, even the
most passionate liberal detractors

00:40:59.230 --> 00:41:05.790
of Richard Nixon, Norman Mailer,
Hunter Thompson, were writing,

00:41:05.790 --> 00:41:10.000
Walter [inaudible], were writing
on his behalf in the '68 campaign

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:13.850
and saying here is a seasoned
steady hand that may be able

00:41:13.850 --> 00:41:17.760
to get us out of Vietnam.

00:41:17.760 --> 00:41:23.060
So I think that his ability to
present himself as a moderate,

00:41:23.060 --> 00:41:28.600
as an experienced man
was what worked in 1960.

00:41:28.600 --> 00:41:32.640
I think the second comeback
is not terribly important.

00:41:32.640 --> 00:41:38.070
I don't think it will make
much difference in history,

00:41:38.070 --> 00:41:41.210
but he really did show some
of himself, for example,

00:41:41.210 --> 00:41:43.840
in the Frost/Nixon debates.

00:41:43.840 --> 00:41:47.480
If you've seen the movie or
the play, there's a moment

00:41:47.480 --> 00:41:52.020
where David Frost very dramatically
takes his clipboard and throws it

00:41:52.020 --> 00:41:55.070
on the floor and says,
"You have to lay more

00:41:55.070 --> 00:41:57.940
of yourself bare here otherwise
you'll never forgive yourself.

00:41:57.940 --> 00:41:59.830
This is your opportunity,"
and he has

00:41:59.830 --> 00:42:01.370
that great moment where
he says, "Yeah.

00:42:01.370 --> 00:42:05.140
I gave them the sword and they
stuck it in and twisted it,

00:42:05.140 --> 00:42:07.600
and I would have done
the same thing myself."

00:42:07.600 --> 00:42:11.580
So, he was never a man
to be underestimated.

00:42:11.580 --> 00:42:15.060
He had great raw political
skills, and like I said,

00:42:15.060 --> 00:42:17.190
that tremendous resilience.

00:42:17.190 --> 00:42:18.490
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: Thank
you for your question.

00:42:18.490 --> 00:42:21.850
Sir, we just had time
for a few more.

00:42:21.850 --> 00:42:23.710
&gt;&gt; Couple of questions.

00:42:23.710 --> 00:42:27.390
The day Richard Nixon
died on April 22nd, '94,

00:42:27.390 --> 00:42:31.060 position:56%
when did you hear the news about it?

00:42:31.060 --> 00:42:32.360
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: I don't know.

00:42:32.360 --> 00:42:33.660
I can't remember.

00:42:33.660 --> 00:42:35.070
Do you remember where you were?

00:42:35.070 --> 00:42:37.210
&gt;&gt; I think -- I was
that home evening.

00:42:37.210 --> 00:42:39.150
[Inaudible].

00:42:39.150 --> 00:42:40.450
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: I was surprised.

00:42:40.450 --> 00:42:42.700
I thought he might live on longer.

00:42:42.700 --> 00:42:44.150
That's a really a Brian
[inaudible] question.

00:42:44.150 --> 00:42:49.570
&gt;&gt; Yes. I was wondering did
you read any of his nine books?

00:42:49.570 --> 00:42:55.140 position:56%
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: I read very closely
his memoir, and I think it's one

00:42:55.140 --> 00:42:57.190
of the best presidential memoirs.

00:42:57.190 --> 00:42:58.490
It's called "RN."

00:42:58.490 --> 00:42:59.790
It's very big and thick.

00:42:59.790 --> 00:43:02.050
And if anything, he goes
too much into Watergate.

00:43:02.050 --> 00:43:05.270
You would think that he would gloss
over it but he really goes in.

00:43:05.270 --> 00:43:08.520
He also wrote another book later
in life called "In the Arena"

00:43:08.520 --> 00:43:12.270 position:56%
which was sort of a secondary memoir

00:43:12.270 --> 00:43:15.340
where he got some digs
in at his enemies.

00:43:15.340 --> 00:43:17.300
But the one that I
enjoyed the most or the two

00:43:17.300 --> 00:43:21.570
that I enjoyed the most were
"Six Crises" which what he wrote

00:43:21.570 --> 00:43:26.040 position:56%
after the 1960 lost and then another
book he wrote about great leaders

00:43:26.040 --> 00:43:28.240
that he had met when
he was president.

00:43:28.240 --> 00:43:30.950
I think it's just called
"Leaders" if I remember correctly.

00:43:30.950 --> 00:43:37.350 position:56%
So RN, Six Crises, and Leaders would
be the three that I would recommend.

00:43:37.350 --> 00:43:38.650
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: Thank you.

00:43:38.650 --> 00:43:39.950
Thank you for your questions.

00:43:39.950 --> 00:43:41.520
Six Crises would certainly be
part of that first comeback.

00:43:41.520 --> 00:43:42.820
Sir?

00:43:42.820 --> 00:43:44.690
&gt;&gt; I'm not sure how much you
discussed Gerald Ford in your book,

00:43:44.690 --> 00:43:47.810
but how would you compare
and contrast Gerald Ford

00:43:47.810 --> 00:43:50.340
as Richard Nixon's VP at a time

00:43:50.340 --> 00:43:55.350
when everyone thought Nixon would
be leaving office versus Mike Pence

00:43:55.350 --> 00:44:00.240 position:56%
as Trump's VP while everyone wonders
how long Trump is going to last.

00:44:00.240 --> 00:44:04.770
Was Ford as acquiescence
as Pence has been?

00:44:04.770 --> 00:44:06.070
&gt;&gt; John Farrell:

00:44:06.070 --> 00:44:09.580
The vice-president's job
is a really tough job,

00:44:09.580 --> 00:44:11.870
and I covered the White House.

00:44:11.870 --> 00:44:17.290
I was a political reporter for a
time before I became a biography.

00:44:17.290 --> 00:44:21.580
And you really have
to feel for them.

00:44:21.580 --> 00:44:24.090
I don't think that Ford
was too acquiescence.

00:44:24.090 --> 00:44:28.100
In the last six months
before Nixon's resignation,

00:44:28.100 --> 00:44:32.130
he was sending signals, and
one of them very famously.

00:44:32.130 --> 00:44:36.300 position:56%
At the time when Nixon was under
fire, he went out and he played golf

00:44:36.300 --> 00:44:40.220
with Tipp O'Neal at a golf
tournament in Massachusetts,

00:44:40.220 --> 00:44:45.220
and Tipp O'Neal was orchestrating
impeachment in the house,

00:44:45.220 --> 00:44:48.880
and allowed the photographers
to take a picture of Ford

00:44:48.880 --> 00:44:51.190
with his arm around Tipp.

00:44:51.190 --> 00:44:57.620
In the last three or four
weeks, he distanced himself,

00:44:57.620 --> 00:45:02.070
did not fall on the
sword with Nixon.

00:45:02.070 --> 00:45:07.340 position:56%
I hesitate to make any comparisons
to Trump and Pence because we're not

00:45:07.340 --> 00:45:11.090
at that same moment
of crisis and drama.

00:45:11.090 --> 00:45:13.740
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: I think we may just
be able to take one more question.

00:45:13.740 --> 00:45:15.290
Thank you, sir, for your question.

00:45:15.290 --> 00:45:16.590
Yes?

00:45:16.590 --> 00:45:21.240
&gt;&gt; Yes. What do you think would
have happened in the '68 election

00:45:21.240 --> 00:45:30.730
if George Wallace was not
a factor and didn't run?

00:45:30.730 --> 00:45:36.300 position:56%
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: I think that in the
end, the number of blue collar votes

00:45:36.300 --> 00:45:47.520
that Wallace took from Humphrey
was less than the number of votes

00:45:47.520 --> 00:45:51.410
that he took from Nixon
in the border states.

00:45:51.410 --> 00:45:57.110
And so, if he had not
run, that would have meant

00:45:57.110 --> 00:46:01.770
that Nixon would have taken those
border states and Humphrey ended

00:46:01.770 --> 00:46:03.820
up taking those northern
states anyway.

00:46:03.820 --> 00:46:06.910
So I think probably Nixon
would have won no matter what.

00:46:06.910 --> 00:46:09.800
His message was not that
different from Wallace's.

00:46:09.800 --> 00:46:12.170
&gt;&gt; Ron Elving: And the deep south,
the states that voted for Wallace.

00:46:12.170 --> 00:46:14.780
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: The deep south
had gone to [inaudible] in 1964

00:46:14.780 --> 00:46:18.600
so the solid democratic staff
had been broken up already.

00:46:18.600 --> 00:46:22.340 position:56%
&gt;&gt; So, the one chance Humphrey might
have had was [inaudible] throw it

00:46:22.340 --> 00:46:24.760
into the house of representatives.

00:46:24.760 --> 00:46:26.750
&gt;&gt; John Farrell: I mean the
big threat to Humphrey was

00:46:26.750 --> 00:46:30.610
that these blue collar
workers in Ohio and Illinois

00:46:30.610 --> 00:46:32.790
and Michigan were going
to go for Wallace,

00:46:32.790 --> 00:46:35.970
and in the end, they did not.

